<DOC><DOCNO> AP880705-0263 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-88 0920EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Switzerland-Fraud     07-05 0195</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Britain-Switzerland-Fraud,0204</SECOND><HEAD>Police Say Massive Fraud Against Swiss Bank Thwarted</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An attempt to defraud the London branch of theUnion Bank of Switzerland of $53 million has been thwarted, policereported.   The City of London Police said in a brief statement Monday nightthe attempted fraud involved the transfer of money from London tothe Swiss town of Nyon through a computer-based switching system.   The police statement gave few other details but the Britishdomestic news agency Press Association said it understood policewere alerted after the transfer of the money triggered acomputerized alarm at the bank in Switzerland.   However, the London newspaper the Daily Telegraph said it wasbelieved a failure in the computer system in Zurich stopped thetransfer being completed before it was discovered.   The Daily Telegraph said the company fraud department of theCity of London Police was called in by the bank last Wednesday.   Police said persons in London and Switzerland were beingquestioned.   The City of London Police is a small force which polices theCity, London's financial district. It operates separately from thelarger Metropolitan Police force, which polices the rest of London.</TEXT></DOC>